  "biography_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Nicander of Colophon II was a Hellenistic prose writer of the 2nd century BCE, distinguished from the more famous poet of the same name. The geographer Strabo identifies him as a writer from Colophon in Asia Minor. No further biographical details survive.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">His only known work is the lost local history titled Colophoniaca. No fragments or specific content from this work are preserved.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">His primary significance lies in his distinction from the poet Nicander. He represents the common Hellenistic tradition of local historiography, and his work, though lost, served as a source for later authors like Strabo.</p>\n</div>",
